  "body": "I'm trying to start geth (v 0.9.29) unlocked with a password stored in a plain text file (the file name is `.password`, stored in the data directory):\n\n```\njack@vent:~/.ethereum$ geth --unlock primary --password .password\nI0613 17:02:50.629035    5713 backend.go:256] Protocol Version: 60, Network Id: 0\nI0613 17:02:50.629088    5713 backend.go:266] Blockchain DB Version: 3\nI0613 17:02:50.631455    5713 chain_manager.go:255] Last block (#555185) 629ee3d578d79b57985493fccd02198c5cc504b8358b080ce1e0705682162f92 TD=3087146347010374\nI0613 17:02:51.262343    5713 cmd.go:148] Starting Geth/v0.9.29/linux/go1.4.2\nI0613 17:02:51.262447    5713 server.go:293] Starting Server\nI0613 17:02:52.695901    5713 udp.go:189] Listening, enode://2bd88c5e9d27eb06b299c6895b2417ef926707860862040569fb8833fe10ff6c719c84d5c26d63b8f988c0798f74d3803cdbe37480f5854390e26ebcdb9293a0@[::]:30303\nI0613 17:02:52.696284    5713 backend.go:475] Server started\nI0613 17:02:52.696271    5713 server.go:530] Listening on [::]:30303\nFatal: Unlock account failed 'Decryption failed: MAC mismatch'\n```\n\nI've double-checked that the password is correct.  (Also have tried using a full path, which also doesn't help.)  This bug only appears when using `--password` in conjunction with `--unlock`; either option works fine by itself.\n\nRelated: which account does `--password` unlock (if any), if you don't specify an account via the `--unlock` flag?  Does it automatically select the etherbase account?  If so, I think in some cases that will be undesirable behavior.\n",
